  "primaryContentSections": [
    {
      "kind": "content",
      "content": [
        {
          "anchor": "overview",
          "level": 2,
          "text": "Overview",
          "type": "heading"
        },
        {
          "type": "paragraph",
          "inlineContent": [
            {
              "type": "text",
              "text": "Nodes are organized hierarchically into node trees, similar to how views and subviews work. Most commonly, a node tree is defined with a scene node ("
            },
            {
              "type": "reference",
              "isActive": true,
              "identifier": "doc://com.apple.documentation/documentation/spritekit/skscene"
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "text": ") as the root node and other content nodes as descendants. The scene node runs an animation loop that processes actions on the nodes, simulates physics, and renders the contents of the node tree for display."
            }
          ]
        },
        {
          "type": "paragraph",
          "inlineContent": [
            {
              "type": "text",
              "text": "Every node in a node tree provides a coordinate system to its children. After a child is added to the node tree, you position it inside its parent’s coordinate system by setting its "
            },
            {
              "type": "reference",
              "isActive": true,
              "identifier": "doc://com.apple.documentation/documentation/spritekit/sknode/1483107-zposition"
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "text": " property. A node’s coordinate system can be scaled and rotated by changing its "
            },
            {
              "type": "reference",
              "isActive": true,
              "identifier": "doc://com.apple.documentation/documentation/spritekit/sknode/1483087-xscale"
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "text": ", "
            },
            {
              "type": "reference",
              "isActive": true,
              "identifier": "doc://com.apple.documentation/documentation/spritekit/sknode/1483046-yscale"
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "text": ", and "
            },
            {
              "type": "reference",
              "isActive": true,
              "identifier": "doc://com.apple.documentation/documentation/spritekit/sknode/1483089-zrotation"
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "text": " properties. When a node’s coordinate system is scaled or rotated, this transformation is applied both to the node’s own content and to that of its descendants."
            }
          ]
        },
        {
          "level": 3,
          "type": "heading",
          "text": "Review Important Properties",
          "anchor": "3044925"
        },
        {
          "type": "paragraph",
          "inlineContent": [
            {
              "type": "text",
              "text": "The "
            },
            {
              "type": "codeVoice",
              "code": "SKNode"
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "text": " class does not perform any drawing of its own. However, many "
            },
            {
              "type": "codeVoice",
              "code": "SKNode"
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "text": " subclasses render visual content and so the "
            },
            {
              "type": "codeVoice",
              "code": "SKNode"
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "text": " class understands some visual concepts:"
            }
          ]
        },
        {
          "type": "unorderedList",
          "items": [
            {
              "content": [
                {
                  "type": "paragraph",
                  "inlineContent": [
                    {
                      "type": "text",
                      "text": "The "
                    },
                    {
                      "type": "reference",
                      "isActive": true,
                      "identifier": "doc://com.apple.documentation/documentation/spritekit/sknode/1483026-frame"
                    },
                    {
                      "type": "text",
                      "text": " property provides the bounding rectangle for a node’s visual content, modified by the scale and rotation properties. The frame is nonempty if the node’s class draws content. Each node subclass determines the size of this content differently. In some subclasses, the size of the node’s content is declared explicitly, such as in the "
                    },
                    {
                      "type": "reference",
                      "isActive": true,
                      "identifier": "doc://com.apple.documentation/documentation/spritekit/skspritenode"
                    },
                    {
                      "type": "text",
                      "text": " class. In other subclasses, the content size is calculated implicitly by the class using other object properties. For example, an "
                    },
                    {
                      "type": "reference",
                      "isActive": true,
                      "identifier": "doc://com.apple.documentation/documentation/spritekit/sklabelnode"
                    },
                    {
                      "type": "text",
                      "text": " object determines its content size using the label’s message text and font characteristics."
                    }
                  ]
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "content": [
                {
                  "type": "paragraph",
                  "inlineContent": [
                    {
                      "type": "text",
                      "text": "A node’s accumulated frame, retrieved by calling the "
                    },
                    {
                      "type": "reference",
                      "isActive": true,
                      "identifier": "doc://com.apple.documentation/documentation/spritekit/sknode/1483066-calculateaccumulatedframe"
                    },
                    {
                      "type": "text",
                      "text": " method, is the largest rectangle that includes the frame of the node and the frames of all its descendants."
                    }
                  ]
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "content": [
                {
                  "type": "paragraph",
                  "inlineContent": [
                    {
                      "type": "text",
                      "text": " Other properties, such as the "
                    },
                    {
                      "type": "reference",
                      "isActive": true,
                      "identifier": "doc://com.apple.documentation/documentation/spritekit/sknode/1483023-alpha"
                    },
                    {
                      "type": "text",
                      "text": " and "
                    },
                    {
                      "type": "reference",
                      "isActive": true,
                      "identifier": "doc://com.apple.documentation/documentation/spritekit/sknode/1483048-hidden"
                    },
                    {
                      "type": "text",
                      "text": " properties, affect how the node and its descendants are drawn."
                    }
                  ]
                }
              ]
            }
          ]
        },
        {
          "type": "paragraph",
          "inlineContent": [
            {
              "type": "text",
              "text": "All nodes are responder objects that can respond directly to user interaction with the node onscreen. See "
            },
            {
              "type": "reference",
              "isActive": true,
              "identifier": "doc://com.apple.documentation/documentation/spritekit/sknode/controlling_user_interaction_on_nodes"
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "text": ". You can also convert between coordinate systems and perform hit testing to determine which nodes a point lies in, and perform intersections between nodes in the tree to determine if their physical areas overlap."
            }
          ]
        },
        {
          "type": "paragraph",
          "inlineContent": [
            {
              "type": "text",
              "text": "Any node in the tree may run "
            },
            {
              "type": "strong",
              "inlineContent": [
                {
                  "type": "text",
                  "text": "actions"
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "text": ", which are used to animate the properties of a node, add or remove nodes, play sounds, or perform other custom tasks. Actions are the heart of the animation system in SpriteKit. See "
            },
            {
              "type": "reference",
              "isActive": true,
              "identifier": "doc://com.apple.documentation/documentation/spritekit/getting_started_with_actions"
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "text": ". "
            }
          ]
        },
        {
          "type": "paragraph",
          "inlineContent": [
            {
              "type": "text",
              "text": "A node can support a physics body, which is an object that simulates the physical properties of the object. When a node has a physics body, the physics simulation automatically computes a new position for the physics body and then moves and rotates the node to match that position. See "
            },
            {
              "type": "reference",
              "isActive": true,
              "identifier": "doc://com.apple.documentation/documentation/spritekit/getting_started_with_physics"
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "text": ". "
            }
          ]
        },
        {
          "type": "paragraph",
          "inlineContent": [
            {
              "type": "text",
              "text": "A node can supply constraints that express relationships with other nodes or locations in the scene. These constraints are automatically applied by the scene before the scene is rendered. Another set of constraints is used in conjunction with actions to perform inverse-kinematic animations. See "
            },
            {
              "type": "reference",
              "isActive": true,
              "identifier": "doc://com.apple.documentation/documentation/spritekit/working_with_inverse_kinematics"
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "text": ". "
            }
          ]
        },
        {
          "level": 3,
          "type": "heading",
          "text": "Ensure Node Access on the Main Thread",
          "anchor": "2985118"
        },
        {
          "type": "paragraph",
          "inlineContent": [
            {
              "type": "text",
              "text": "All of the SpriteKit callbacks for "
            },
            {
              "type": "reference",
              "isActive": true,
              "identifier": "doc://com.apple.documentation/documentation/spritekit/skviewdelegate"
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "text": ", "
            },
            {
              "type": "reference",
              "isActive": true,
              "identifier": "doc://com.apple.documentation/documentation/spritekit/skscenedelegate"
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "text": ", and "
            },
            {
              "type": "reference",
              "isActive": true,
              "identifier": "doc://com.apple.documentation/documentation/spritekit/skscene"
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "text": " occur in the main thread and therefore, these are safe places to access or manipulate nodes. If you are performing other work in the background, you should adopt an approach similar to "
            },
            {
              "type": "reference",
              "isActive": true,
              "identifier": "doc://com.apple.documentation/documentation/spritekit/sknode/getting_started_with_nodes#2985117"
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "text": "."
            }
          ]
        },
